WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.029 --> 00:00:06.240
Prof: What is scripture,
and what is canon?

00:00:06.240 --> 00:00:09.120
These are not necessarily the
same thing.

00:00:09.120 --> 00:00:11.721
When you call something
"scripture,"

00:00:11.721 --> 00:00:14.957
what you simply mean is it's
some kind of writing that is

00:00:14.957 --> 00:00:17.790
taken by somebody as holy and
authoritative,

00:00:17.790 --> 00:00:18.690
somehow sacred.
 

00:00:18.690 --> 00:00:21.629
Now, different religions--some
religions don't have what we

00:00:21.629 --> 00:00:23.960
would normally think of as
scripture, in Islam,

00:00:23.960 --> 00:00:25.380
Judaism or Christianity.
 

00:00:25.380 --> 00:00:27.652
They might have lots and lots
of holy writings,

00:00:27.652 --> 00:00:30.023
but they don't have a
particular, bounded body of

00:00:30.023 --> 00:00:31.900
writings that they call
scripture.

00:00:31.900 --> 00:00:33.320
They have lots of scripture.
 

00:00:33.320 --> 00:00:36.304
What makes something scripture,
though, is that it's taken to

00:00:36.304 --> 00:00:39.140
be authoritative and holy by
some particular community.

00:00:39.140 --> 00:00:43.434
Now, notice that does not
necessarily mean it's canonical

00:00:43.434 --> 00:00:47.653
because scripture in some
religions refers to a bunch of

00:00:47.653 --> 00:00:48.420
stuff.
 

00:00:48.420 --> 00:00:52.790
But they don't have a set list
of things that make something

00:00:52.790 --> 00:00:53.680
the canon.
 

00:00:53.680 --> 00:00:57.751
Judaism, Islam and Christianity
all have, basically,

00:00:57.751 --> 00:00:58.470
canons.
 

00:00:58.470 --> 00:01:00.890
That is it's the Qur'an for
Islam.

00:01:00.890 --> 00:01:04.078
It's the Hebrew Bible for
Judaism.

00:01:04.078 --> 00:01:06.441
And it's the Hebrew Bible,
plus the New Testament--and

00:01:06.441 --> 00:01:08.360
we'll talk about some of the
other writings,

00:01:08.360 --> 00:01:09.430
too--for Christians.
 

00:01:09.430 --> 00:01:11.554
What does it mean to call
something "canon"

00:01:11.554 --> 00:01:13.230
that makes it different from
scripture?

00:01:13.230 --> 00:01:16.426
By calling it canon,
we're saying there's an actual

00:01:16.426 --> 00:01:20.006
list that a religion body
adheres to, with books that are

00:01:20.006 --> 00:01:22.500
either in or books that are not
in.

00:01:22.500 --> 00:01:24.683
So "scripture"
can refer to any kind of

00:01:24.683 --> 00:01:27.320
writing that a bunch of people
consider holy or inspired or

00:01:27.320 --> 00:01:28.140
authoritative.
 

00:01:28.140 --> 00:01:30.132
But when you call something
"canon,"

00:01:30.132 --> 00:01:32.747
you mean that there's a group
of writing that has boundaries

00:01:32.747 --> 00:01:33.190
to it.
 

00:01:33.190 --> 00:01:36.992
And, of course,
it just comes from the Greek

00:01:36.992 --> 00:01:41.328
word canon,
spelled with one "n,"

00:01:41.328 --> 00:01:42.390
not two.
 

00:01:42.390 --> 00:01:44.050
This Greek word means a list.
 

00:01:44.050 --> 00:01:45.660
It can mean a rod, a staff.
 

00:01:45.660 --> 00:01:47.050
It can mean a measuring rod.
 

00:01:47.050 --> 00:01:51.087
And so it comes to be a list
that accounts as authoritative

00:01:51.087 --> 00:01:52.760
in early Christianity.
 

00:01:52.760 --> 00:01:56.830
So that's what it means to call
something "canonical."

00:01:56.830 --> 00:01:59.290
When you talk about something
like the Shakespeare canon,

00:01:59.290 --> 00:02:01.376
the canon of Shakespeare or the
canon of great Western

00:02:01.376 --> 00:02:03.896
Literature that's actually using
the term in a bit of an expanded

00:02:03.896 --> 00:02:04.290
sense.
 

00:02:04.290 --> 00:02:07.790
Because we don't really
consider Western Literature to

00:02:07.790 --> 00:02:11.288
have an actual closed canon of
authoritative texts.

00:02:11.288 --> 00:02:14.482
In Christianity,
though, it means the list of

00:02:14.482 --> 00:02:18.545
texts that are scripture and
recognized as different from

00:02:18.545 --> 00:02:19.780
other things.
 

00:02:19.780 --> 00:02:22.159
We have to first,
also, recognize that the early

00:02:22.159 --> 00:02:23.288
Christians,
it seems like,

00:02:23.288 --> 00:02:25.480
from the very early period,
at least a lot of them,

00:02:25.480 --> 00:02:27.780
accepted Jewish scripture as
their own.

00:02:27.780 --> 00:02:29.995
So for example,
when the Apostle Paul says,

00:02:29.995 --> 00:02:33.001
"Scripture says,"
he's not talking about the New

00:02:33.001 --> 00:02:33.740
Testament.
 

00:02:33.740 --> 00:02:35.960
He's talking about Jewish
scripture.

00:02:35.960 --> 00:02:37.985
So almost all the early
Christians, they didn't

00:02:37.985 --> 00:02:40.758
know--the people writing the New
Testament didn't know they were

00:02:40.758 --> 00:02:42.080
writing the New Testament.
 

00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:45.218
They just thought they were
writing a gospel or a sermon or

00:02:45.218 --> 00:02:47.060
a letter or something like that.
 

00:02:47.060 --> 00:02:48.819
So when you see the term
"scripture"

00:02:48.819 --> 00:02:51.330
in the New Testament,
every time except,

00:02:51.330 --> 00:02:53.720
maybe, one time--
and we'll talk about this when

00:02:53.720 --> 00:02:55.693
we get to it--
it refers to Jewish scripture

00:02:55.693 --> 00:02:59.169
that Christians accepted,
followers of Jesus accepted,

00:02:59.169 --> 00:03:00.180
as their own.
 

00:03:00.180 --> 00:03:02.930
The oldest materials that we
have for Christianity--

00:03:02.930 --> 00:03:06.082
and so what the lecture today
is going to be about is how did

00:03:06.082 --> 00:03:09.026
the particular twenty-seven
books that came to be the New

00:03:09.026 --> 00:03:12.310
Testament canon,
how did those get chosen?

00:03:12.310 --> 00:03:13.939
By whom--who made the decision?
 

00:03:13.939 --> 00:03:15.378
When did they make the decision?
 

00:03:15.378 --> 00:03:17.158
And what were the criteria they
used?

00:03:17.158 --> 00:03:19.720
Why did they allow some books
in and other books not in?

00:03:19.720 --> 00:03:22.989
The oldest written materials of
Christianity are actually the

00:03:22.989 --> 00:03:23.970
letters of Paul.
 

00:03:23.970 --> 00:03:26.370
This may come as a surprise,
because you get to the gospels

00:03:26.370 --> 00:03:27.568
first in the New Testament.
 

00:03:27.568 --> 00:03:29.113
And most people assume,
"Oh, the gospels,

00:03:29.113 --> 00:03:30.280
they're about the life of
Jesus.

00:03:30.280 --> 00:03:31.460
That must be the oldest
stuff."

00:03:31.460 --> 00:03:34.448
Well, the gospels are actually
all written after the letters of

00:03:34.448 --> 00:03:36.280
Paul were written by 20 or 30
years.

00:03:36.280 --> 00:03:39.690
So the oldest material we have
are the letters of Paul.

00:03:39.690 --> 00:03:44.152
And the oldest one of those
letters is 1 Thessalonians,

00:03:44.152 --> 00:03:48.699
probably, dated to around the
year 50 or thereabouts.

00:03:48.699 --> 00:03:51.105
Pretty quickly,
though, different churches,

00:03:51.105 --> 00:03:54.026
probably Paul's churches,
initially, started sending

00:03:54.026 --> 00:03:56.090
around copies of Paul's letters.
 

00:03:56.090 --> 00:03:58.190
Remember, there's no printing
press in the ancient world.

00:03:58.190 --> 00:04:00.778
Whenever your church would get
a copy of one of these letters

00:04:00.778 --> 00:04:02.490
from Paul,
you would have scribes,

00:04:02.490 --> 00:04:04.496
often slaves,
because slaves were especially

00:04:04.496 --> 00:04:05.460
trained to be scribes.
 

00:04:05.460 --> 00:04:07.812
They would take that letter,
and they would make a copy of

00:04:07.812 --> 00:04:08.020
it.
 

00:04:08.020 --> 00:04:10.205
And then, they might keep the
original, and they'd send the

00:04:10.205 --> 00:04:11.258
copy off to somebody else.
 

00:04:11.258 --> 00:04:13.092
Or they might keep the copy and
send the original off to

00:04:13.092 --> 00:04:13.460
somebody.
 

00:04:13.460 --> 00:04:16.596
And so letters would be copied,
and books would be copied and

00:04:16.596 --> 00:04:18.740
sent around from different
communities.

00:04:18.740 --> 00:04:20.319
This obviously happened.
 

00:04:20.319 --> 00:04:22.559
In Colossians 4:16,
which is actually,

00:04:22.559 --> 00:04:25.949
I'll argue, not written by
Paul, although it claims to be

00:04:25.949 --> 00:04:27.160
written by Paul.
 

00:04:27.160 --> 00:04:29.480
The writer says,
"When this letter has been

00:04:29.480 --> 00:04:31.012
read among you,
have it read,

00:04:31.012 --> 00:04:32.990
also, in the church of the
Laodiceans,

00:04:32.990 --> 00:04:35.303
and see that you read,
also, the letter from

00:04:35.303 --> 00:04:36.220
Laodicea."
 

00:04:36.220 --> 00:04:39.199
So notice this author--who I
think is a pseudepigrapher.

00:04:39.199 --> 00:04:40.910
He's writing in the name of
Paul, but not really Paul.

00:04:40.910 --> 00:04:43.673
He's saying that there's
another letter sent by Paul to

00:04:43.673 --> 00:04:44.850
the Laodicean church.
 

00:04:44.850 --> 00:04:47.954
So let them send you their
copy, and you send a copy of

00:04:47.954 --> 00:04:49.220
this letter to them.
 

00:04:49.220 --> 00:04:52.838
So we quickly see that even in
the letters under Paul's name,

00:04:52.838 --> 00:04:55.129
this activity's being spread
around.

00:04:55.129 --> 00:04:57.367
Also, we see the letter of
Ephesians--again,

00:04:57.367 --> 00:04:59.968
claims to be by Paul,
but I'll argue is not by Paul

00:04:59.968 --> 00:05:02.829
when we get to that lecture,
way into the semester.

00:05:02.829 --> 00:05:05.322
The letter to the Ephesians
looks like it was not actually

00:05:05.322 --> 00:05:06.588
written to only one church.
 

00:05:06.588 --> 00:05:09.927
It looks like it was a circular
letter meant to be circulated to

00:05:09.927 --> 00:05:11.040
different churches.
 

00:05:11.040 --> 00:05:12.439
And one of the ways we think
this--

00:05:12.439 --> 00:05:15.648
one of the reasons we think
this is because in some of the

00:05:15.648 --> 00:05:18.983
old manuscripts of Ephesians,
"To the Ephesians"

00:05:18.983 --> 00:05:19.750
is not there.
 

00:05:19.750 --> 00:05:22.339
It's either blank or it's to
somebody else.

00:05:22.339 --> 00:05:25.151
So some scholars have suggested
that maybe the letter to the

00:05:25.151 --> 00:05:27.870
Ephesians was originally
intended as a circular letter.

00:05:27.870 --> 00:05:29.730
And, maybe, the original
writer, sort of,

00:05:29.730 --> 00:05:32.569
even left some copies blank so
that somebody could fill in.

00:05:32.569 --> 00:05:34.680
"Oh, well,
we're in Laodicea.

00:05:34.680 --> 00:05:36.952
Let's say 'To the Laodiceans,'
and we can act like Paul sent it

00:05:36.952 --> 00:05:37.649
just to us."
 

00:05:37.649 --> 00:05:40.562
So the manuscript tradition
suggests that it was a letter

00:05:40.562 --> 00:05:42.589
that was a circular letter in
itself.

00:05:42.589 --> 00:05:46.540
We also have imitations of
Paul's letters developing.

00:05:46.540 --> 00:05:48.392
For example,
I said, Colossians I don't

00:05:48.392 --> 00:05:50.880
think is written by Paul,
but by a disciple of Paul,

00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:52.149
maybe after his death.
 

00:05:52.149 --> 00:05:55.829
Ephesians was written by a
different disciple of Paul,

00:05:55.829 --> 00:05:59.035
and he was using as his model
for a Pauline letter the actual

00:05:59.035 --> 00:06:01.389
letters of Paul,
or at least some of them that

00:06:01.389 --> 00:06:02.588
he possessed and knew of.
 

00:06:02.588 --> 00:06:04.559
But he was, also,
using the letter to the

00:06:04.559 --> 00:06:05.199
Colossians.
 

00:06:05.199 --> 00:06:08.497
So notice this guy,
another guy sort of forging

00:06:08.497 --> 00:06:10.290
another letter by Paul.
 

00:06:10.290 --> 00:06:13.569
And he's using another forged
letter by Paul as his model.

00:06:13.569 --> 00:06:15.959
In fact, he almost quotes it in
places.

00:06:15.959 --> 00:06:18.408
So we can tell that the writer
of the Ephesians seems to have

00:06:18.408 --> 00:06:19.470
been a different author.
 

00:06:19.470 --> 00:06:23.160
But he used the letter to the
Colossians as one of his models.

00:06:23.160 --> 00:06:26.319
So Paul's letters were being
imitated, new ones were being

00:06:26.319 --> 00:06:28.649
written, and they were being
circulated.

00:06:28.649 --> 00:06:32.930
Paul's letters actually became
so famous and respected,

00:06:32.930 --> 00:06:35.089
and at least in some aspects of
early Christianity,

00:06:35.089 --> 00:06:36.430
that they were called
themselves

00:06:36.430 --> 00:06:37.470
"scripture."
 

00:06:37.470 --> 00:06:39.538
And this is the one exception I
said to when in the New

00:06:39.538 --> 00:06:41.682
Testament you see the word
scripture, it refers to Jewish

00:06:41.682 --> 00:06:42.220
scripture.
 

00:06:42.220 --> 00:06:44.663
The guy who wrote 2
Peter--again,

00:06:44.663 --> 00:06:48.302
not really Peter,
but a writer writing in Peter's

00:06:48.302 --> 00:06:50.541
name--
talked about Paul's letters as

00:06:50.541 --> 00:06:52.480
if--and he calls them scripture.
 

00:06:52.480 --> 00:06:54.420
He says, "There are many
things in Paul's letters very

00:06:54.420 --> 00:06:55.290
difficult to understand.
 

00:06:55.290 --> 00:06:57.470
And some people twist them to
their own destruction as they do

00:06:57.470 --> 00:06:58.649
other kinds of scripture."
 

00:06:58.649 --> 00:07:01.310
So already by the time 2 Peter
was written,

00:07:01.310 --> 00:07:04.220
which was much later than the
letters of Paul,

00:07:04.220 --> 00:07:08.053
Paul's letters have come to be
regarded by at least some early

00:07:08.053 --> 00:07:10.379
Christians as scripture
themselves.

00:07:10.379 --> 00:07:13.665
So collections of Paul's
letters were gradually being

00:07:13.665 --> 00:07:15.750
made and copied and circulated.
 

00:07:15.750 --> 00:07:20.153
That's the first development of
what you have a collection of

00:07:20.153 --> 00:07:24.410
what would be considered holy
writing among Christians that

00:07:24.410 --> 00:07:27.639
was more than just the Jewish
scripture.

00:07:27.639 --> 00:07:30.795
We also know,
though, about oral traditions

00:07:30.795 --> 00:07:32.300
in Paul's letters.
 

00:07:32.300 --> 00:07:34.810
And this gets us back to how
did the gospels come about?

00:07:34.810 --> 00:07:36.540
So Paul's letters came about
that way.

00:07:36.540 --> 00:07:38.500
How did the gospels come about?
 

00:07:38.500 --> 00:07:41.149
We know that there were oral
traditions about Jesus.

00:07:41.149 --> 00:07:43.550
People would tell stories about
Jesus in their churches.

00:07:43.550 --> 00:07:45.779
Sometimes, they would tell
sayings.

00:07:45.779 --> 00:07:50.024
So in Romans 12:14,
Paul says, "Bless those

00:07:50.024 --> 00:07:51.829
who persecute you.
 

00:07:51.829 --> 00:07:53.829
Bless and do not curse
them."

00:07:53.829 --> 00:07:57.579
Now, he doesn't say this is a
quotation of Jesus.

00:07:57.579 --> 00:08:01.696
But it sounds an awful lot like
you find in some of the gospels,

00:08:01.696 --> 00:08:03.199
like in Matthew 5:44.
 

00:08:03.199 --> 00:08:06.267
So Paul's saying this,
probably, passing this along as

00:08:06.267 --> 00:08:07.600
a quotation of Jesus.
 

